Hugh & Jenx, I don’t think this is an example of “invisible” weaving, at least not the one described in the Marino/Benford paper. It’s a “visible” imperfection (passage error) in the weaving, as would be expected from any manual weaving process. The same with the variable thickness of the warp threads, both are considered evidence against a medieval weaving. Please check pages 11-15 of this reference;
http://editionsassailly.com/books/The%20Shroud.pdf
It’s a beautiful, very balanced, read and is available online for free. I find the textile portion very informative.
